{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657731"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20643"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20643"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94168"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77268"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11712"},{"type":"tags","id":"12531"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32288"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94168"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which phagocytes kill ingested microbes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct degradation by cathepsin proteases","Acidification of the phagolysosome by proton pumps","Production of reactive oxygen species by NADPH oxidase","Depletion of essential nutrients from the phagosome","Secretion of antimicrobial peptides into the bloodstream"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of reactive oxygen species by NADPH oxidase\u003C/strong\u003E represents the primary mechanism by which phagocytes kill ingested microbes. This process, also known as the respiratory burst, involves the assembly of the multicomponent NADPH oxidase enzyme complex on the phagosomal membrane. The enzyme reduces oxygen to superoxide anion (O\u2082\u207b), which is then converted to hydrogen peroxide (H\u2082O\u2082). In neutrophils, myeloperoxidase (MPO) converts H\u2082O\u2082 to hypochlorite (HOCl), a potent antimicrobial agent. These reactive oxygen species damage microbial lipids, proteins, and nucleic acids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect degradation by cathepsin proteases\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to the breakdown of microbial components after killing, but these proteases are not the primary killing mechanism. They function mainly to degrade already-killed microbes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcidification of the phagolysosome by proton pumps\u003C/strong\u003E does occur and creates an optimal environment for lysosomal enzymes, but it is not the primary killing mechanism. The acidic environment supports the activity of acid hydrolases but is insufficient alone to kill most pathogens.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDepletion of essential nutrients from the phagosome\u003C/strong\u003E may contribute to microbial growth inhibition (e.g., through lactoferrin binding iron), but it is not the primary killing mechanism. Most microbes are actively killed rather than starved to death.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of antimicrobial peptides into the bloodstream\u003C/strong\u003E is not how phagocytes typically function. Antimicrobial peptides like defensins and cathelicidins act primarily within the phagolysosome or in the immediate extracellular environment, not systemically in the bloodstream.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to ROS, phagocytes also utilize reactive nitrogen species, particularly nitric oxide (NO) produced by inducible nitric oxide synthase (iNOS). NO reacts with superoxide to form peroxynitrite (ONOO\u207b), which is highly toxic to microbes. The importance of both mechanisms is demonstrated by the observation that mice lacking either NADPH oxidase or iNOS are only mildly susceptible to infections, while those lacking both succumb rapidly to infections by normally harmless bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reactive oxygen species (ROS) are the primary mechanism by which phagocytes kill ingested microbes.","NADPH oxidase (phagocyte oxidase) is a multicomponent enzyme that produces superoxide anion, which is converted to hydrogen peroxide and other microbicidal substances.","Nitric oxide (NO) produced by inducible nitric oxide synthase (iNOS) combines with superoxide to form peroxynitrite, which damages microbial structures.","Lysosomal enzymes including myeloperoxidase, defensins, and proteases contribute to microbial killing within phagolysosomes."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 81-83"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77268"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77268"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T13:04:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T13:06:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94168"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co